00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:14.139
The Millenium Project was a very far-out idea
in the late or mid-1980's.

00:01:14.139 --> 00:01:21.090
Thought was that the year 2000 would occur
and journalists would stick microphone down

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:25.529
the throats of various futurists around the
world and say, "Okay, tell me everything about

00:01:25.529 --> 00:01:28.659
the next thousand years." or something silly
like that.

00:01:28.659 --> 00:01:34.369
And we were worried that, if we had too much
to drink the night before, we might not say

00:01:34.369 --> 00:01:37.791
anything useful, and we may waste an opportunity
in the year 2000.

00:01:37.791 --> 00:01:43.810
So the thought was, we should create some
system -- some idea -- that was important

00:01:43.810 --> 00:01:46.650
for one generation, or one millennium gift
to the next.

00:01:46.650 --> 00:01:51.289
And the thought was to create a global participatory
think tank for humanity.

00:01:51.289 --> 00:01:55.549
There are tons of think tanks for countries.
There's think tanks for ideologies.

00:01:55.549 --> 00:01:59.249
There's think tanks for water.
There's think tanks for all kinds of stuff,

00:01:59.249 --> 00:02:03.939
but there was no think tank for we human beings
as a whole.

00:02:03.939 --> 00:02:08.849
Now, you could say, "Well, doesn't the World
Bank do that?" Yes, but they do it for economics.

00:02:08.849 --> 00:02:12.360
Or don't say the World -- what about the CIA?
Well, the CIA does it for United States.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:16.239
But where do you go to get a picture of the
whole game?

00:02:16.239 --> 00:02:23.019
And this was during the Cold War, so it was
not exactly an easy task.

00:02:23.019 --> 00:02:31.219
Fortunately, the Cold War ended when we started.
We started officially in 1996, after a three-year

00:02:31.219 --> 00:02:33.760
feasibility study.
I don't know if there's ever been a three-year

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:36.109
feasibility study for anything other than
the Millennium Project.

00:02:36.109 --> 00:02:43.060
And then that was -- before that was a one-year
feasibility study to answer the question that

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:47.660
the United Nations University asked us to
answer, which was, "Somebody must be trying

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:51.439
to do this already."
I mean, it's an obvious idea to have a bunch

00:02:51.439 --> 00:02:54.090
of futurists around the world collaborating
to figure out the whole game.

00:02:54.090 --> 00:02:57.060
That's an obvious idea, it must be done by
somebody.

00:02:57.060 --> 00:02:59.849
And so far, we couldn't find anybody, so we
started it.

00:02:59.849 --> 00:03:04.439
So how do you create a think tank on behalf
of humanity?

00:03:04.439 --> 00:03:08.280
We decided that it had to be pulled together
by U.N. systems -- you know, U.N.

00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:14.439
University, UNESCO, U.N.D.P.
But also it involved with governments.

00:03:14.439 --> 00:03:19.960
The first funding actually came from the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency for the feasibility

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:28.480
study.
NGOs -- corporations -- and woe, how did we

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:32.230
do that?
We jumped too quickly. Be right back here.

00:03:32.230 --> 00:03:40.920
Okay.
Where's my little thing? There we go. All

00:03:40.920 --> 00:03:42.879
right â€“
So the Millennium Project was put together

00:03:42.879 --> 00:03:47.769
by U.N. organizations, governments, NGOs,
corporations, and universities.

00:03:47.769 --> 00:03:52.610
The idea was that, if we're going to do this
on behalf of humanity, it ought to cut across

00:03:52.610 --> 00:03:55.450
all these institution categories.
It can't be just an academic exercise.

00:03:55.450 --> 00:03:58.519
It can't be just a political thing.
It can't be just an NGO thing.

00:03:58.519 --> 00:04:04.829
It had to be cutting across the systems.
So we operate as what we call a 'trans-institution'.

00:04:04.829 --> 00:04:11.760
Now, there's no such thing legally as a trans-institution.
We hope that we'll get some country to amend

00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:17.910
their corporate law -- you've got nonprofit
law, profit law, and we want to have trans-institution

00:04:17.910 --> 00:04:22.889
law.
By a 'trans-institutional law' and registered

00:04:22.889 --> 00:04:27.490
as a trans-institution, what we mean is that
all the people doing the work, or whatever

00:04:27.490 --> 00:04:32.210
it is -- whether it's for AIDS or ours happen
to be for the future, improving education,

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:35.920
whatever it happens to be -- that the people
doing the work ought to come from each of

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:38.740
these institutional categories, but not a
majority of any one.

00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:42.300
The money should come from all these institutional
categories, but not a majority of any one.

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:45.870
The governing body of the organization should
come from all these categories, but not a

00:04:45.870 --> 00:04:50.520
majority of any one.
And you should prove value at the end of the

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:54.940
year in annual report or some activity to
show that you've produced value for all these

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:59.330
institutional categories.
Now, the trans-institution is extremely efficient

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:04.220
entity.
I think it will be a new kind of institution

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:07.870
in the future.
We've got all kinds of innovations in software,

00:05:07.870 --> 00:05:12.280
in medicine, aerodynamics, but we don't have
much innovation in institutional design.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:18.860
And I think this is one of them.
Because when you want to act, you can act

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:22.240
through any one of these categories.
When you want to do some of your water work,

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:25.940
you can act through UNESCO, or the U.N. system,
for example.

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:29.580
If you want to do some collective intelligence
work -- which we'll talk about -- maybe you

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:34.460
can act through Google.
But then you're also acted on by all these

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:37.419
categories.
So when the Millennium Project does work,

00:05:37.419 --> 00:05:41.510
it wants to be influenced by all these institutional
categories and it wants to act through all

00:05:41.510 --> 00:05:45.900
those institutional categories.
Key element here is they should be self-organizing.

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:51.160
If I assign somebody to do it, then I got
to manage them, but these should be people

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:53.830
who -- One, they should be attracted to the
activity.

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:57.690
So you can't have every corporation involved.
You can't have every government involved.

00:05:57.690 --> 00:06:01.270
It's too complex.
But those that want to play, let them self-select

00:06:01.270 --> 00:06:05.740
so that you have enthusiasm and you get better
synergies this way.

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:11.551
Now, we have mini trans-institutions -- not
perfect -- but mini ones around the world

00:06:11.551 --> 00:06:16.350
that are called 'nodes.' And when I use the
word 'node,' I mean an intersection of two

00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:19.930
or more networks.
So there's networks of government players.

00:06:19.930 --> 00:06:23.710
There's networks of corporate players.
There's networks of university players.

00:06:23.710 --> 00:06:28.159
Where they intersect, we call a node.
And we have a node here in Silicon Valley.

00:06:28.159 --> 00:06:33.690
Jack Park is a member here in the audience.
And some others in the area are working on

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:36.690
venture capital, software, and the things
of Silicon Valley.

00:06:36.690 --> 00:06:40.990
So the idea is, this becomes a brain-picking
system for the Millennium Project.

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:45.000
How do you pick the brains of the world?
Well, this is our answer to that.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.630
It's also our answer to -- you hear people
talk about "Global local" all the time.

00:06:49.630 --> 00:06:52.449
This is our management answer to how you do
global/local.

00:06:52.449 --> 00:06:56.660
So that we can send a question out to these
nodes -- or these 33 nodes around the world

00:06:56.660 --> 00:07:00.449
 -- and say, "Who knows the most about water?"
for example.

00:07:00.449 --> 00:07:03.630
Each of these nodes -- the node is composed
of these different categories, so they can

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:07.139
say, "Okay, who knows the most in universities?
Who knows the most in corporations?

00:07:07.139 --> 00:07:10.280
Who knows the most in NGOs?
Who knows the most in the U.N. representatives

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:12.800
here?
Who knows the most?" And then, since they're

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:17.729
doing it in their own cultures, they're talking
to them in Farsi or Hebrew or whatever language

00:07:17.729 --> 00:07:20.590
it happens to be.
And they're doing the recruitment.

00:07:20.590 --> 00:07:25.330
So I'm not telling who should be in; they're
telling us who should be in.

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:34.970
All right. So these nodes then is the factor
for a participatory process.

00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:40.659
They also can be headquarters for something.
For example, the tech awards here in Silicon

00:07:40.659 --> 00:07:47.560
Valley was a spin-off of the Millennium Project.
And when the tech awards got going for innovations

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:52.941
in the five categories, we said -- some of
our players in the node here in Silicon Valley

00:07:52.941 --> 00:07:56.650
said, "Well, we ought to do something with
all these finalists in these tech awards."

00:07:56.650 --> 00:08:01.509
So then, they help get business planning.
So it was just to get an award and some publicity

00:08:01.509 --> 00:08:06.430
and applause, they now get venture capital,
business management training, innovations

00:08:06.430 --> 00:08:11.620
from a lot of hot shots here in Silicon Valley.
But that's a contribution to the whole world.

00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:14.439
Each of these nodes is like a headquarters
for something else.

00:08:14.439 --> 00:08:20.969
In Mexico City, they run a similar contest
for how to address the 15 global millennium

00:08:20.969 --> 00:08:25.830
challenges -- which I'll talk about in a second
 -- with high school students around the world.

00:08:25.830 --> 00:08:28.759
In Korea -- and I'll talk a little bit more
about that -- they're wanting to put together

00:08:28.759 --> 00:08:33.250
a global climate change situation room.
And hopefully we'll maybe collaborate with

00:08:33.250 --> 00:08:37.840
someone here in Google, or at least we'll
use your products in how to create a collective

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:40.080
intelligence for a global climate change situation
room.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:43.820
And if we do that correctly, that'll be something
that all the other nodes can share and maybe

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:47.750
the U.N. systems as well.
So this is sort of the management structure

00:08:47.750 --> 00:08:53.010
of the Millennium Project.
We have two categories of things that the

00:08:53.010 --> 00:08:56.210
project produces.
One is methods.

00:08:56.210 --> 00:08:59.730
This is Future Research Methodology version
3.0.

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:04.570
It has 39 chapters.
More than half of the chapters have been written

00:09:04.570 --> 00:09:09.880
by the author of the method -- or the inventor
of the method -- or someone who's contributed

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:14.200
significantly to that methods evolution.
It's about 1,300 pages.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:18.120
It's the largest collection of methods to
explore the future international peer review

00:09:18.120 --> 00:09:20.920
that's ever been assembled anywhere and there's
not even a close second.

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:26.270
So for those here in Google looking at future
trends and future ideas and what's next and

00:09:26.270 --> 00:09:28.950
all that sort of stuff, here's some methods
you may want to look through to see if there's

00:09:28.950 --> 00:09:31.320
something in there that you haven't used that
you might be able to use.

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:35.330
The other is the state of the future.
That's the content part.

00:09:35.330 --> 00:09:40.390
And that looks like a report or a book.
It's also a management technique for us, because

00:09:40.390 --> 00:09:43.900
I had worked for right wing, left wing, up
wing, down wing think tanks and I was tired

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:47.840
of the nonsense that if one think tank says
it, then another think tank says, "Well, they've

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:54.170
got to be wrong."
We all know that every think tank's got some

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:57.260
sort of value.
So we ought to create something across the

00:09:57.260 --> 00:09:59.331
board, which is part of the evolution of the
Millennium Project.

00:09:59.331 --> 00:10:04.720
But one of the things that weren't being done
was, think tanks would do a report, and then

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:08.070
they would do another study, another report
 -- another study, another report.

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:11.920
Or some would get together some big thing
like the Club of Rome or the inter-futures

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:16.130
or some big thing, big applause, and there's
no cumulative wisdom going on.

00:10:16.130 --> 00:10:20.270
There's no system to improve the improvement
of the improvement system.

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:24.610
There's no systematic approach to that.
So we figured we would have to do a "State

00:10:24.610 --> 00:10:29.760
of the Future" report each year.
And then, we would have to make sure that

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:34.390
that report is better than last year.
So what we write about water this year has

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:36.870
to be more important than what I wrote about
last year.

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:39.350
So there's 13 of these things have been done
so far.

00:10:39.350 --> 00:10:44.100
So anybody can see, Is there an evolution
of knowledge and better precision and so forth,

00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:46.810
or not?
So this is our own sort of self-evaluation

00:10:46.810 --> 00:10:49.430
tool.
It comes in two parts.

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:54.190
One is about a hundred pages, very short summaries
of various things for people to look at that

00:10:54.190 --> 00:11:00.051
are too busy to do the academic research.
And then, the CD ROM that's got 6,700 pages.

00:11:00.051 --> 00:11:05.320
So those who want the short version, you go
to print.

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:08.310
And those who want the details behind the
research -- What did the invitation letter

00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:09.871
look like?
What did the questionnaire look like?

00:11:09.871 --> 00:11:16.100
What was the demographics?
all the detail behind it -- is in the CD ROM.

00:11:16.100 --> 00:11:25.210
So we began by saying, "What's happening in
the world that is going to become a very big

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:37.630
thing in, say, 25 years that is either not
known generally or is misunderstood?

00:11:37.630 --> 00:11:42.000
What's going on? And what's that going to
look like in ten years?

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:45.910
And what's that going to look like in 25 years?
And give us a reference."

00:11:45.910 --> 00:11:51.240
So it wasn't just an opinion survey.
People had to do some work to bring in ideas.

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:58.040
And we collected something like 280 developments.
And went through a long, tortuous process

00:11:58.040 --> 00:12:00.800
of interviewing policymakers and feedback
systems.

00:12:00.800 --> 00:12:04.510
And I won't bore you with that.
We ended up with 15 issues.

00:12:04.510 --> 00:12:09.600
And our planning committee said, "That's nice.
You acted like engineers.

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:12.410
You've identified all these issues or problems.
What about all the opportunities?

00:12:12.410 --> 00:12:15.780
What about the good stuff?"
So the next year, we did the same sort of

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:18.390
process of having people ask these questions
all around the world and doing the interviews.

00:12:18.390 --> 00:12:25.910
We ended up with almost the same number -- 280-some-odd
developments of good things that were important

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:28.980
 -- either misunderstood or not known -- that
could evolve in the future.

00:12:28.980 --> 00:12:31.670
Then the third year, we put the two together
into the challenges.

00:12:31.670 --> 00:12:36.680
And then one of the people -- one of the planning
committee members from Finland said, "Look,

00:12:36.680 --> 00:12:42.710
stop changing please. We like your framework.
We use it in our Committee for the Future

00:12:42.710 --> 00:12:47.250
in Parliament to do our evaluation.
If you keep changing it, it's difficult for

00:12:47.250 --> 00:12:48.740
us."
So we haven't changed.

00:12:48.740 --> 00:12:51.670
We kept the 15 challenges since then up to
the present tense.

00:12:51.670 --> 00:12:56.580
We may still change them, but so far, we think
it's the best framework to understand what's

00:12:56.580 --> 00:12:59.520
happening in the world.
First challenge -- and I won't go into detail

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:01.960
in all of these things.
There's just too much information, but you

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:05.710
can get it in the State of the Future.
the first -- and by the way, when I say 'first,'

00:13:05.710 --> 00:13:13.120
it is not the most important.
All 15 of these challenges are important,

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:17.790
just like your brain is important and your
heart is important and one is not more important

00:13:17.790 --> 00:13:20.460
than the other.
But when you study biology, you know, you

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:22.650
get to list down the systems.
So we're listing down these systems.

00:13:22.650 --> 00:13:26.270
This is a system. They're interdependent.
If you improve one, you help the others. If

00:13:26.270 --> 00:13:29.930
you hurt one, you hurt the others.
This is the system. This is the agenda for

00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:34.690
humanity, but it's a system.
So don't get lost in the idea that your preferred

00:13:34.690 --> 00:13:38.580
challenge is number six on the list.
They're all a hundred percent important.

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:43.580
So how can sustainable development be achieved
by all, while addressing global climate change?

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:48.880
As you know that we probably consume more
material on the Earth since World War II than

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:53.190
all the years in the past.
You all know all the issues of sustainability

00:13:53.190 --> 00:13:56.940
 -- I don't need to tell you.
We cannot continue as we are.

00:13:56.940 --> 00:14:01.730
One of the issues, though, that we'd like
more people to take seriously is this 'parts

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:08.050
per million' people talk about in carbon.
It has been discussed, Should we have 550

00:14:08.050 --> 00:14:11.810
parts per million carbon in the atmosphere,
or should it be 450?

00:14:11.810 --> 00:14:18.570
It is now about 391 parts per million, and
we already have major ice areas of the Andes

00:14:18.570 --> 00:14:21.670
and the Himalayas and so forth around the
world going down.

00:14:21.670 --> 00:14:26.460
And that means that rivers change -- dry up.
It means that farming changes.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:29.660
It means, if we got mass migration coming
up, we got serious stuff.

00:14:29.660 --> 00:14:34.300
So 390 parts per million is not sustainable
now.

00:14:34.300 --> 00:14:40.450
To say that we have 450, to me, is a sham.
When people say it's politically -- we can't

00:14:40.450 --> 00:14:44.450
do a better job than that politically, I'm
going, "Well, you know, nature doesn't care

00:14:44.450 --> 00:14:49.650
about the politics with all due respect."
So for those of you involved in the Climate

00:14:49.650 --> 00:14:54.980
Change Conference, I hope you hold to the
350 mark rather than the 450 mark.

00:14:54.980 --> 00:14:59.540
How could we have enough water for everybody
without conflict?

00:14:59.540 --> 00:15:06.230
As some of you may know -- Frank does, I'm
sure -- over 40 percent of humanity gets its

00:15:06.230 --> 00:15:16.230
water today from sources, watersheds, that
are controlled by two or more countries.

00:15:16.230 --> 00:15:20.511
And that's not necessarily so bad by itself,
but you take the next fact, and it's a real

00:15:20.511 --> 00:15:24.160
problem.
The water tables -- the water layer underneath

00:15:24.160 --> 00:15:29.470
the ground -- on all continents are going
down and have been going down for some years.

00:15:29.470 --> 00:15:34.140
This is a very serious prescription for conflict
 -- continuing conflict.

00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:39.350
In China and India, what -- 40 percent of
humanity -- they're having very serious water

00:15:39.350 --> 00:15:43.920
problems.
Our node chair in China was involved in those

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:50.870
water scenarios ten years ago.
And they had good case/best case/worst case/middle

00:15:50.870 --> 00:15:54.170
case scenarios.
And in China, the water scenarios in China

00:15:54.170 --> 00:16:00.910
 -- it showed that the situation in China
would get worse the next 15 to 17 years in

00:16:00.910 --> 00:16:08.230
the best case scenario.
Meaning that another 20 years, you're as bad

00:16:08.230 --> 00:16:12.290
off as you are now, but you got a lot more
people.

00:16:12.290 --> 00:16:17.120
So holding political stability in China and
India -- it's going to be extremely difficult

