00:32:28.750 --> 00:32:31.489
person is working on illegal drug traffic,
this person's working on this.

00:32:31.489 --> 00:32:36.090
But what is the integrated global strategy?
Another task -- another challenge for us.

00:32:36.090 --> 00:32:40.299
How can the global energy demands be safely
and efficiently met?

00:32:40.299 --> 00:32:45.730
How can scientific and technological breakthroughs
be accelerated to improve the human condition?

00:32:45.730 --> 00:32:52.539
And how can ethical considerations become
more routinely incorporated into global decisions?

00:32:52.539 --> 00:32:58.999
This is the agenda put together by over 13,
14, 15 years of various futurists and policy

00:32:58.999 --> 00:33:05.289
people around the world.
This is what we got to get done.

00:33:05.289 --> 00:33:09.200
Now, one of the first challenge in dealing
with climate change.

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:14.820
I'm very pleased to say the Millennium Project
has been asked to help create the global climate

00:33:14.820 --> 00:33:20.109
change situation room in South Korea.
We did a little study a couple of years ago

00:33:20.109 --> 00:33:24.899
on how you would create a collective intelligence
to address energy.

00:33:24.899 --> 00:33:30.509
And so, we may be using that model and apply
that to the situation room being created in

00:33:30.509 --> 00:33:34.230
South Korea.
And we would invite any of the employees in

00:33:34.230 --> 00:33:38.919
Google to play with us.
Because as you all know, you may design a

00:33:38.919 --> 00:33:41.799
system, but when you get into it, you try
to improve it.

00:33:41.799 --> 00:33:46.869
So we hope by the time we actually put the
situation room together, it'll be a real collective

00:33:46.869 --> 00:33:49.230
intelligence that all in the world can draw
on.

00:33:49.230 --> 00:33:53.080
It will be a physical situation room, but
the collective intelligence behind it should

00:33:53.080 --> 00:33:56.309
be available to everybody.
And so, we have more and more people involved

00:33:56.309 --> 00:34:00.621
in this, because this is a human family issue.
But the nice thing about the situation room

00:34:00.621 --> 00:34:05.100
 -- ______ think from just collective intelligence
 -- is that you also are taking a look at

00:34:05.100 --> 00:34:08.690
what governments say they're doing, what the
policies are, what the gaps are, what the

00:34:08.690 --> 00:34:11.850
limitations are, what the status is.
So that you're actually getting on phones

00:34:11.850 --> 00:34:15.490
and getting arm twisters to move it.
So the purpose of the situation was to manage

00:34:15.490 --> 00:34:19.110
something.
We don't have -- you can do a Google search

00:34:19.110 --> 00:34:23.450
on this -- we don't have, to my knowledge,
a situation room.

00:34:23.450 --> 00:34:29.179
And if you find it, I want to know it -- a
situation room to manage the global climate

00:34:29.179 --> 00:34:32.870
change management issues.
We've got the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate

00:34:32.870 --> 00:34:37.679
Change, but that's science, research, collaboration,
with a political veneer laid on top of it.

00:34:37.679 --> 00:34:43.071
But where do you go to see the whole situation?
I know, you've got to go to Google to see

00:34:43.071 --> 00:34:45.500
the whole situation.
But let's -- maybe we can work together on

00:34:45.500 --> 00:34:49.050
this one.
All right. What do I mean by 'collective intelligence'?

00:34:49.050 --> 00:34:52.429
I mean an emergent property first of all.
It's not a thing itself.

00:34:52.429 --> 00:34:56.810
It's not all of us sitting here making decision.
I don't mean that as collective intelligence.

00:34:56.810 --> 00:35:00.640
I mean it's an emergent property.
It's something that isn't there when you start

00:35:00.640 --> 00:35:05.930
to do it.
It emerges from the synergies among data knowledge

00:35:05.930 --> 00:35:13.290
information, hardware/software experts, that
continually learns from feedback to produce

00:35:13.290 --> 00:35:17.350
nearly adjusted time knowledge for better
decisions than those actions -- than those

00:35:17.350 --> 00:35:21.220
elements acting alone.
That's what I mean when I say, 'collective

00:35:21.220 --> 00:35:24.240
intelligence' -- emergent properties.
So imagine creating a collective intelligence

00:35:24.240 --> 00:35:28.100
for climate change.
It's an emergent property and keeps growing

00:35:28.100 --> 00:35:31.160
and improving through time.
And then you're cooking it up to decision

00:35:31.160 --> 00:35:34.200
makers for actions, like a situation room
should do.

00:35:34.200 --> 00:35:37.620
One of the -- this is an abstract version
of maybe an interface.

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:44.030
We may or may not do it this way, but this
is one of the ideas -- is that we find continually

00:35:44.030 --> 00:35:47.761
that people get lost in detail and forget
the big picture.

00:35:47.761 --> 00:35:52.360
And the big picture people sometimes don't
know enough detail to make the right decisions.

00:35:52.360 --> 00:35:55.090
So this is the quandary.
So one of the things, We want to have information

00:35:55.090 --> 00:36:00.240
displayed so they can always see where the
piece fits into the whole all the time.

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:03.610
This is one of the ideas.
These may be three columns or four columns,

00:36:03.610 --> 00:36:05.780
maybe different ways of doing the searches,
but this is one.

00:36:05.780 --> 00:36:10.630
The idea here is, How do you create a user
interface so as people do their searches -- as

00:36:10.630 --> 00:36:14.390
they do their work -- they're seeing how the
part relates to the whole?

00:36:14.390 --> 00:36:19.370
Another aspect of this is that -- let's say
for example, here's an information unit, or

00:36:19.370 --> 00:36:23.100
a piece of information about photovoltaic
efficiency.

00:36:23.100 --> 00:36:27.860
What we would like is that that piece of information
is linked to the column on the right-hand

00:36:27.860 --> 00:36:29.772
side.
First would be the overview.

00:36:29.772 --> 00:36:33.660
Let me jump ahead and come back in a second.
By overview, there's an old antique software

00:36:33.660 --> 00:36:35.600
called CM1.
Some of you may remember it.

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:41.210
There's a way if you have a question like,
"How do you make photovoltaics more efficient?

00:36:41.210 --> 00:36:44.810
What are the three or four different categories
of research on that?

00:36:44.810 --> 00:36:48.150
What are the pro and cons from each of this?
And what are the references behind it?

00:36:48.150 --> 00:36:52.700
Why?" Because people need to see the whole
picture, but they can't be overloaded by all

00:36:52.700 --> 00:36:57.170
the detail.
So this would be one kind of approach to having

00:36:57.170 --> 00:36:59.700
an overview of an issue.
So you went back up here.

00:36:59.700 --> 00:37:04.860
So a piece of information would be linked
to its overview.

00:37:04.860 --> 00:37:06.710
Second, what are the problems and opportunities?
Where do they come from?

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:10.150
Well, we'd have groups of networks that the
Millennium Project would organize around the

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:12.050
world.
They would be doing discussion in various

00:37:12.050 --> 00:37:15.720
collaborative systems, and we would be able
to identify the problems and opportunities

00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:18.110
through that.
We'd also be doing research, What's the data

00:37:18.110 --> 00:37:23.341
in forecast about that piece of information?
Are there computer simulations that you can

00:37:23.341 --> 00:37:24.910
run?
What are the expert ratings?

00:37:24.910 --> 00:37:28.230
We -- the Millennium Project has developed
a software called Realtime Delphites, a polling

00:37:28.230 --> 00:37:32.840
system that updates from realtime so that
we could constantly update among experts rating

00:37:32.840 --> 00:37:36.590
on a new piece of information as it comes
in and rank-order them, by the way, in the

00:37:36.590 --> 00:37:39.220
display system.
What are the unresolved issues?

00:37:39.220 --> 00:37:44.520
As they rate these -- if you have a bipolar
distribution, that's clearly an unresolved

00:37:44.520 --> 00:37:48.800
issue, so it would be empirical on that.
And we'd have open, non-peer-reviewed information

00:37:48.800 --> 00:37:56.380
as well.
More open -- more contemporary view here is

00:37:56.380 --> 00:38:02.020
the issues-based information system that we
will probably be using.

00:38:02.020 --> 00:38:08.840
But the idea is to keep track of how the conversation
goes in an organized, logical structure.

00:38:08.840 --> 00:38:12.080
One of the problems with blogs is that people
repeat themselves -- it's one thing after

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:15.070
another, after another, after another, after
another; it's a pain in the neck -- whereas

00:38:15.070 --> 00:38:21.620
this way, you would have the information being
edited if all goes well in these units -- each

00:38:21.620 --> 00:38:24.580
is a wiki by itself.
It's going to a wiki point by itself.

00:38:24.580 --> 00:38:28.740
So that the overview of an issue is continually
updated.

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:31.820
So it's not a database unit that sits there
dead in the water.

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:36.430
It's dynamic itself.
Another is for the decision maker players.

00:38:36.430 --> 00:38:39.970
We want to be able to create some dashboards
